00:23:25.119 --> 00:23:30.479
the project and what it's trying to do, that's where there's the divergence.

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:39.040
But I can admit that trying to explain that to people on LinkedIn or on X or Blue Sky or

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:42.880
something can be a little bit tricky. So yeah, to get back to the question,

00:23:42.959 --> 00:23:48.239
what got me interested in the space originally, I was really just frustrated with the fact that I

00:23:48.239 --> 00:23:53.760
was a huge fan of Polars. I really liked using Polars. I really liked contributing to Polars.

00:23:54.400 --> 00:24:01.199
But then one of the most frequent complaints I heard from prospective users was that when they

00:24:01.199 --> 00:24:07.040
went to use their favorite data science tools, they either had to convert everything to Pandas

00:24:07.839 --> 00:24:12.880
or the tool would claim to support Polars, but under the hood, it was just converting to Pandas.

00:24:13.599 --> 00:24:18.000
There are some cases when that's okay. You really don't see the effect of it,

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:27.520
but there are cases when the performance penalty can be quite large, like converting a string to

00:24:27.520 --> 00:24:32.560
object in Pandas can be quite expensive. There are some data types that don't exactly match.

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:40.959
And perhaps one that I really felt strongly about in terms of missed opportunities was that Polars

00:24:40.959 --> 00:24:47.520
has both a lazy and an eager API, whereas Pandas is purely eager. So having to convert everything

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:52.719
to Pandas, when there were some operations which could in principle have been done lazily,

00:24:54.079 --> 00:24:58.719
it really felt like a missed opportunity. It felt like it should have been possible to do much

00:24:58.719 --> 00:25:05.359
better. And I could see that some libraries were doing what you were doing in Great Tables,

00:25:05.359 --> 00:25:09.839
Michael, where you had your own hand-rolled compatibility layer. Scikit-learn was doing

00:25:09.839 --> 00:25:15.760
something similar. HP Plot had their compatibility layers for QDF and Dask and others.

00:25:17.199 --> 00:25:20.160
There were some other libraries that were doing similar things. So I just figured,

00:25:20.160 --> 00:25:25.199
well, let's try to make something reusable. And we need to choose a common API.

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:33.920
Originally, I thought about using the Pandas API, but I found that it was a bit frustrating to try

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:42.400
to transpile Polars to Pandas, whereas doing it in the other way around, it just worked beautifully.

00:25:43.280 --> 00:25:49.599
The Polars API is stricter than Pandas. And arguably, when it comes to doing transpilation,

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:56.479
it's easier to start from users writing something in a stricter API,

00:25:57.040 --> 00:26:04.800
and then transpiling that to the less strict one. Also, Pandas has the concept of an index

00:26:04.800 --> 00:26:09.839
that Polars doesn't have. So if the user does not have to write index code directly,

00:26:10.400 --> 00:26:15.599
then that's one less thing to worry about. So I just tried this. And you can see in the early

00:26:15.599 --> 00:26:20.640
commit messages in novels before I released it, when I was just writing it by myself as a

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:25.439
little one-person experiment, the commit messages start saying things like,

00:26:25.439 --> 00:26:29.680
ooh, it works! Getting there! Three exclamation marks. I was really excited at first.

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:35.839
At some point, I published it online and started enforcing pull requests and reviews and all of

00:26:35.839 --> 00:26:40.800
that. But for better or for worse, those early commit messages that I was just writing to myself

00:26:41.359 --> 00:26:44.800
are still there in the project history. But it's actually not too bad to see the

00:26:45.599 --> 00:26:50.160
excitement that I was feeling at the beginning when I realized that actually transpiling Polars,

00:26:52.239 --> 00:26:59.119
translating Polar syntax to Pandas was fairly satisfying. So really, that was the original

00:26:59.119 --> 00:27:04.400
motivation, just trying to solve this ecosystem problem where we had all of these really nice

00:27:04.400 --> 00:27:12.239
data frames out there. But frustratingly, the data science ecosystem was locked in to Pandas.

00:27:12.239 --> 00:27:16.880
The first time I presented novels, after having showed it on a call to Michael,

00:27:17.439 --> 00:27:23.920
was at PyCon Lithuania in 2023. And I ended the presentation by saying that my hope for

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:29.280
the next year was that we would see the data science ecosystem become less locked into Pandas,

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:36.239
and that maybe we would also see Duolingo add a Lithuanian course. And only one of these things

00:27:36.239 --> 00:27:41.199
happened. I think there's still no way to learn Lithuanian on Duolingo, but hopefully they'll

00:27:41.199 --> 00:27:46.479
address that as well. I'm super curious to hear about, to go back to Wes's question,

00:27:46.479 --> 00:27:53.680
how you got into some of this. And also, I know Narwhals has this really active Discord community.

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:59.839
I'd be really curious to hear some of the outreach you did. How did you get involved,

00:27:59.839 --> 00:28:05.680
and what did you do early on to build out the Narwhals community? Because it's a happening

