Yeah, there is some truth to this. I realized when I published my first open source project

00:33:38.239 --> 00:33:46.239
back during the initial COVID outbreak, it was called NBQA. It was a little quality assurance

00:33:46.239 --> 00:33:52.640
tool for Jupyter Notebooks. At the time, my assumption was that if you published a tool

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:57.599
and it had a bug, somebody would open an issue and tell you about it, and then you fixed the bug,

00:33:57.599 --> 00:34:02.000
and then it would be better for everyone else. And that's when I realized, no, most people,

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:07.119
if they try a tool and they find a bug, they uninstall it and they move on to something else

00:34:07.119 --> 00:34:15.199
without even reporting the bug. But GitHub makes it easy to just do a site-wide search for mentions

00:34:15.199 --> 00:34:20.320
of keywords. So just searching around for mentions of the word, I started seeing issues that people

00:34:20.320 --> 00:34:25.520
were running into that they weren't even reporting. I just figured, ah, this is so valuable. This is

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:30.560
so useful. I can address these things. And so when I started Narwhals, I was just already

00:34:31.919 --> 00:34:37.040
used to having to proactively look for issues that people might be encountering

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:43.760
rather than relying on them to report things. So yes, I would just do GitHub searches for mentions

00:34:43.760 --> 00:34:50.560
of Narwhals. Fortunately, Narwhals is a fairly unique name. So most mentions that came up were

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:56.320
exactly of this project. And if I saw projects saying, oh, yeah, we should maybe consider

00:34:56.320 --> 00:35:01.600
looking into this Narwhals project, I was just so keen on getting the ball rolling

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:08.080
that I would show them how it could be done, or in some cases, even open a pull request to them

00:35:08.080 --> 00:35:13.520
showing, hey, here's a proof of concept of how you can Narwhalify your code base.

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:19.360
And that was so valuable. You just realize so many things about your tool once you actually start

00:35:19.360 --> 00:35:26.639
trying to use it to solve a problem. The dogfooding process is just so valuable.

00:35:27.360 --> 00:35:32.239
For anyone wanting to start a tool, that's probably the best thing you can do to make

00:35:32.239 --> 00:35:36.479
it usable. Just try using it yourself for an extended period of time.

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:43.280
Yeah. Yeah, I love that. And I will say, I know we got some experience of that, too,

